MIT Media Lab Director Joi Ito on Innovation







The availability of open-source software and the low cost of communications and collaboration technologies have made Silicon Valley-like innovation less risky for large, established companies.

On March 11, 2011, when entrepreneur and venture capitalist Joi Ito was interviewing for his current job as director of the MIT Media Lab, an earthquake and tsunami rocked his birth country of Japan. Seeking accurate and trustworthy information about the 9.0 magnitude quake and its impact on the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear power plant, Ito tapped the power of the internet and organized dozens of friends, colleagues, and strangers online.
Members of the skunkworks group pooled their skills. Using open-source software, hardware, and other components, they built and deployed more than 1,000 Geiger counters to detect the amount of radiation exposure from the damaged power plant. Volunteers in Japan installed the devices on cars and drove around the country collecting data. Over the last five years, the counters have gathered 48 million data points, creating, according to Ito’s estimate, the largest open data set in the world.
“When we undertook this effort, government officials criticized us, saying, ‘You’re amateurs. What do you know about nuclear emissions?’ But we ended up beating every government agency and non-governmental organization in terms of the volume and quality of our work, and we did it with very little money—about $150,000 in funding from the Knight Foundation, a Kickstarter campaign, and individual donors,” says Ito. “Many of the scientists who initially questioned us later wanted to collaborate.”
This effort, which grew into the open-citizen science initiative Safecast, exemplifies what Ito calls an engineering-driven innovation model, in which individuals with a desire to build something can do so relatively quickly and easily by capitalizing on free and open-source software and low-cost communication and collaboration technologies. Ito says this innovation model appears repeatedly in the consumer internet space and is moving into the manufacturing and industrial internet sectors as well.
The engineering-driven innovation model contrasts with the MBA-driven approach many large, established companies use, in which, according to Ito, innovation teams write proposals and make presentations in order to get permission and funding. He understands big companies take a more conservative approach because the level of risk is so much higher than for entrepreneurs and venture capitalists. “In big companies, you worry about downside: You might exceed your budget. The market might flip over,” he says. “In contrast, I have no fear when I invest money in a company because the top two performing organizations in my portfolio are each worth more than the rest of the portfolio combined. This approach allows me to amplify winners and write off losers. That’s very different from the circumstances in large companies.”
Given the low cost of innovation today, the risk is lower than big companies realize. For that reason, Ito believes companies should reconsider their attachment to the MBA-driven approach to innovation and embrace the engineering-driven model.
Ito points out that engineering-driven innovation is transforming smaller factories in Shenzhen, China, and urges American manufacturers to take note. He says the entrepreneurial mindset and passion for learning among factory workers in Shenzen have given them the ability to move seamlessly from, say, textile manufacturing to electronics, and has led some to develop new smartphones. One factory worker developed a phone that retails for $8 with many of the features—including an OLED screen, lithium battery, MP3 player, and SMS texting capability—consumers expect from high-end products. “These workers are literally sitting on the factory floor designing prototypes,” says Ito. “Their motto is, ‘If you don’t have tooling grease under your fingernails, you’re not a real designer.’ They’re a force to be reckoned with. You don’t get this kind of innovation when a designer and manufacturing engineer have to exchange PowerPoint presentations.”
The next major innovation Ito urges executives to watch is synthetic biology, in which principles and practices from biology and engineering are combined to redesign existing biological components and systems, and even fabricate new ones. DuPont’s Sorona® biopolymer fiber is an example—Ito says it’s now created using a microbe that converts amino acids and sugars to fabric materials 30 percent more efficiently than traditional manufacturing methods. In other areas of synthetic biology, engineers are “reprogramming” bacteria to produce a range of products, including biofuels and arsenic sensors.
While Ito is enthusiastic about synthetic biology, he sounds a warning about one area of innovation currently garnering much attention: the blockchain. He believes the distributed ledger technology will reinvent many aspects of financial services, but the billion dollars’ worth of venture money flowing into the space has put the industry “ahead of its skis” and led to the creation of some unreasonably aggressive or poorly designed businesses. He urges developers to focus on the stability, security, and fundamental theory behind the technology and to proceed with caution.
“In the past, if you wanted to develop a new product or service from the bottom up, it would have cost millions to billions of dollars,” says Ito. “Now the cost of innovation is so low that you no longer need money as much as you need capabilities.”
 
