                  		Related Deloitte Insights
                  	



IT’s Transformation Journey Continues

                          IT has already undergone considerable evolution, but there’s still much more to come. The next phase of transformation will likely put new focus on the way IT operates, how it collaborates with business and external partners, and how its development teams can work smarter and more efficiently to deliver services.
                        



Manufacturing USA: The Power of the Ecosystem

                          How can any one organization keep up with the ever-increasing pace of technological change? Join forces to create an ecosystem and work together for more efficient innovation. That’s one of many lessons to be learned from the example of Manufacturing USA, which now includes 14 technology-focused institutes.
                        



Fintech Innovation in ‘Silicon Wadi’

                          Tel Aviv, Israel, has emerged as a leading technology development hub. Many startups there are pushing the bounds of fintech, and incubators are providing the support they need for knowledge-sharing, collaboration, innovation, and a digitally enabled employee experience.
                        

















                  		Editors Choice
                  	



A Time of Change, Growth for CIOs

                          A confluence of disruptive forces is straining current IT operating models, prompting many CIOs to craft new strategies, structures, and processes to transform IT’s engagement with the business and deliver more value. The effect of these changes is likewise disrupting the CIO role, forcing CIOs to thinking deeply about the personal attributes and behaviors they will need to succeed.
                        



The Hard but Important Work of Technology Strategy

                          Narrowly defined, utilitarian IT strategies are a thing of the past. Many C-level leadership teams and CIOs are now hard at work crafting complex, ambitious technology strategy and transformation plans in lockstep with the business. Peter Vanderslice, a principal with Deloitte Consulting LLP and co-lead of the CIO Program, shares his perspectives on these efforts. Spoiler alert: There are no shortcuts.
                        



9 Competencies Help CIOs Become Business Leaders

                          Businesses need CIOs to move beyond traditional back-office operational tasks to bring more value to the enterprise. Competencies that help CIOs improve operational excellence, develop leadership talents, and build entrepreneurial skills enable them to transition from technology leaders to business leaders.
                        







              		About Deloitte Insights
              	

Deloitte Insights for CIOs couples broad business insights with deep technical knowledge to help executives drive business and technology strategy, support business transformation, and enhance growth and productivity. Through fact-based research, technology perspectives and analyses, case studies and more, Deloitte Insights for CIOs informs the essential conversations in global, technology-led organizations. Learn more
























































