Dave Ball



Wow, where to begin?
It is nice to say that newspapers have “a double bottom line”, but unless the editor is also the owner, that’s pretty naive.  Unlike in tech, where investors may put money in a portfolio of startups hoping that one in ten (or twenty or one hundred) makes it, you’ll find that the investors in media properties tend to make one big bet, and they only see one bottom line.  Public companies are also challenged to hit hit their revenue and profit numbers each quarter.  That may be good … it may be bad … but that’s the way it is.  That’s the environment that management is working in.
As far as product development goes, perhaps the editors are not the people who should be the innovators, exactly because of the skill set.  In other industries, CPG for instance, there is a rigorous methodology for product development.  Is there a market?  How big is the market?  Who are the competitors?  Can we make money (yes, that is a consideration)?
Seems like the folks at Blackberry (and Motorola?) had the same constraints as people in media.  Maybe it’s just easier to innovate when you are not the industry under attack.












 






